(34, 3, 'The financial cost of returning artifacts would be prohibitively expensive for both parties'),
(34, 4, 'Returning objects to their countries of origin would expose them to potential damage or destruction'),
(35, 1, 'It establishes important legal precedents for international property disputes'),
(35, 2, 'It has significant implications for the financial sustainability of major Western museums'),
(35, 3, 'It threatens to fundamentally transform the global tourism industry'),
(35, 4, 'It represents a broader reckoning with colonialism''s legacy and is a prerequisite for cultural revival'),
(36, 1, 'transfer full ownership of contested objects to their countries of origin unconditionally'),
(36, 2, 'provide originating countries with high-quality replicas while retaining the original artifacts'),
(36, 3, 'balance the interests of both parties while acknowledging the cultural sovereignty of originating communities'),
(36, 4, 'create comprehensive digital archives that allow virtual access to artifacts from anywhere in the world');

